window.docContents[69].resolve({"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-Hasse-bound/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-Hasse-bound--The-Hasse-Bound":{"contents":"(Hasse's theorem.) For an elliptic curve  () over a finite field\n whose point set is finite, with trace of Frobenius\n (, ),\n\nequivalently .\nFormalised in Hasse-Weil (private repo — link requires access): hasse_bound\n(HasseWeil/HasseBound.lean#L85, commit 1aa7429) — in progress. The pure-algebra reduction\n and the discriminant argument are sorry-free; two\ndeferred witnesses remain (each guarding a true integer statement): the non-negativity of the\ndegree quadratic form on  inside traceOfFrobenius_sq_le\n(HasseBound.lean#L72) and the point-count identity  in\npointCount_eq (Frobenius.lean#L331).\n\nWrite  for the Frobenius isogeny () and consider the\nendomorphism  for . The degree map on  is a\npositive semi-definite quadratic form (Silverman III.6.3), so\n\nThe non-negativity of this binary form forces its discriminant : substituting\n,  and clearing gives  (trace_sq_le_four_mul_deg, a one-line\nnlinarith once the form is known non-negative). Taking square roots,\n (abs_le_two_sqrt_of_sq_le, using ). Combining with\n (pointCount_eq) yields the displayed bound (hasse_bound).\nIn the formalisation the quadratic-form non-negativity and the point-count identity are the two\nremaining deferred witnesses, each parametrised so that the top-level bound is sorry-free\nconditional on them (hasse_bound_of_all_witnesses).\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elliptic Curves and Arithmetic Geometry\u0009The Hasse bound","header":"7.11.3. The Hasse Bound","id":"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-Hasse-bound/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-Hasse-bound--The-Hasse-Bound"}});